{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630866"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:20:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:20:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17324"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17324"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.02,0.71,0.11,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10014"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108910"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10014"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17324"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91279"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3846"},{"type":"tags","id":"3848"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5479"},{"type":"tags","id":"11065"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35967"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40660"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108910"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDiethylstilbestrol is a synthetic oestrogen that was prescribed to pregnant women from the 1940s to the early 1970s to prevent miscarriage and other pregnancy complications. In the 1970s, epidemiological studies identified a strong association between maternal use of this medication during pregnancy and the development of a rare form of cancer in female offspring.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following malignancies is most strongly associated with in utero diethylstilbestrol exposure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vaginal squamous cell carcinoma","Cervical adenocarcinoma","Vaginal clear cell adenocarcinoma","Endometrial adenocarcinoma","Ovarian clear cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDiethylstilbestrol (DES) is a synthetic oestrogen that was widely prescribed to pregnant women from the 1940s to the early 1970s. In the 1970s, epidemiological studies revealed a strong causal relationship between maternal DES use during pregnancy and the development of \u003Cstrong\u003Evaginal clear cell adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E in female offspring, typically occurring in young women aged 15-30 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDES acts as an endocrine disruptor during critical periods of foetal development, causing structural abnormalities in the reproductive tract of exposed female offspring. These abnormalities include vaginal adenosis (presence of glandular tissue in the vagina) and structural changes to the cervix and uterus. The clear cell adenocarcinoma typically arises from these areas of adenosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaginal squamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common type of vaginal cancer overall, but it typically occurs in older women and is not associated with DES exposure. It is more commonly linked to human papillomavirus infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in DES-exposed women, but the association is much weaker than with vaginal clear cell adenocarcinoma. The primary risk factors for cervical adenocarcinoma remain human papillomavirus infection and other traditional risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometrial adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E has been studied in DES-exposed women, but the evidence for increased risk is limited and inconsistent compared to the strong association with vaginal clear cell adenocarcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian clear cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is not significantly associated with DES exposure. This cancer type has different risk factors and typically occurs in older women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe discovery of this association led to the withdrawal of DES from use in pregnancy and highlighted the importance of long-term follow-up studies for medications used during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Diethylstilbestrol (DES) is a synthetic oestrogen that was used in pregnancy until the 1970s to prevent miscarriage.","In utero exposure to DES causes structural abnormalities in the reproductive tract of female offspring.","DES exposure in utero is strongly associated with the development of vaginal clear cell adenocarcinoma in young women."],"references":["Melnick S, Cole P, Anderson D, Herbst A. Rates and Risks of Diethylstilbestrol-Related Clear-Cell Adenocarcinoma of the Vagina and Cervix. New England Journal of Medicine. 1987 Feb 26;316(9):514\u20136."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91279"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17324"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91279"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-14T19:12:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-14T19:14:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10014"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108910"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"posit